[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] The classical example of unsupervised learning in the study of neural networks is Donald Hebb's principle, that is, neurons that fire together wire together.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] In Hebbian learning, the connection is reinforced irrespective of an error, but is exclusively a function of the coincidence between action potentials between the two neurons.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] A similar version that modifies synaptic weights takes into account the time between the action potentials (spike-timing-dependent plasticity or STDP).
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] Hebbian Learning has been hypothesized to underlie a range of cognitive functions, such as pattern recognition and experiential learning.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] Among neural network models, the self-organizing map (SOM) and adaptive resonance theory (ART) are commonly used in unsupervised learning algorithms.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] The SOM is a topographic organization in which nearby locations in the map represent inputs with similar properties.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] The ART model allows the number of clusters to vary with problem size and lets the user control the degree of similarity between members of the same clusters by means of a user-defined constant called the vigilance parameter.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] ART networks are used for many pattern recognition tasks, such as automatic target recognition and seismic signal processing.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] Two of the main methods used in unsupervised learning are principal component and cluster analysis.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] Cluster analysis is used in unsupervised learning to group, or segment, datasets with shared attributes in order to extrapolate algorithmic relationships.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] Cluster analysis is a branch of machine learning that groups the data that has not been labelled, classified or categorized.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] Instead of responding to feedback, cluster analysis identifies commonalities in the data and reacts based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] This approach helps detect anomalous data points that do not fit into either group.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] A central application of unsupervised learning is in the field of density estimation in statistics, though unsupervised learning encompasses many other domains involving summarizing and explaining data features.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] It can be contrasted with supervised learning by saying that whereas supervised learning intends to infer a conditional probability distribution conditioned on the label of input data; unsupervised learning intends to infer an a priori probability distribution .
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] Some of the most common algorithms used in unsupervised learning include: (1) Clustering, (2) Anomaly detection, (3) Approaches for learning latent variable models.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] One of the statistical approaches for unsupervised learning is the method of moments.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] In the method of moments, the unknown parameters (of interest) in the model are related to the moments of one or more random variables, and thus, these unknown parameters can be estimated given the moments.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] The moments are usually estimated from samples empirically.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] The basic moments are first and second order moments.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] For a random vector, the first order moment is the mean vector, and the second order moment is the covariance matrix (when the mean is zero).
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] Higher order moments are usually represented using tensors which are the generalization of matrices to higher orders as multi-dimensional arrays.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] In particular, the method of moments is shown to be effective in learning the parameters of latent variable models.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] Latent variable models are statistical models where in addition to the observed variables, a set of latent variables also exists which is not observed.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] A highly practical example of latent variable models in machine learning is the topic modeling which is a statistical model for generating the words (observed variables) in the document based on the topic (latent variable) of the document.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] In the topic modeling, the words in the document are generated according to different statistical parameters when the topic of the document is changed.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] It is shown that method of moments (tensor decomposition techniques) consistently recover the parameters of a large class of latent variable models under some assumptions.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] The Expectation–maximization algorithm (EM) is also one of the most practical methods for learning latent variable models.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] However, it can get stuck in local optima, and it is not guaranteed that the algorithm will converge to the true unknown parameters of the model.
[src:self-supervised-learning/unsupervised-learning] In contrast, for the method of moments, the global convergence is guaranteed under some conditions.
